%N A390674 Numbers k > 0 such that the k-th composition in standard order has all equal first sums.
%C A390674 First differs from A353744 in lacking 37, corresponding to the composition (3,2,1).
%C A390674 The k-th composition in standard order (graded reverse-lexicographic, A066099) is obtained by taking the set of positions of 1's in the reversed binary expansion of k, prepending 0, taking first differences, and reversing again. This gives a bijective correspondence between nonnegative integers and integer compositions.
%C A390674 The first sums of a nonempty sequence (a, b, c, d, ...) are (a+b, b+c, c+d, ...).
%H A390674 Gus Wiseman, <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vTCPiJVFUXN8IqfLlCXkgP15yrGWeRhFS4ozST5oA4Bl2PYS-XTA3sGsAEXvwW-B0ealpD8qnoxFqN3/pub">Statistics, classes, and transformations of standard compositions</a>
%e A390674 The terms together with standard compositions begin:
%e A390674    1: (1)
%e A390674    2: (2)
%e A390674    3: (1,1)
%e A390674    4: (3)
%e A390674    5: (2,1)
%e A390674    6: (1,2)
%e A390674    7: (1,1,1)
%e A390674    8: (4)
%e A390674    9: (3,1)
%e A390674   10: (2,2)
%e A390674   12: (1,3)
%e A390674   13: (1,2,1)
%e A390674   15: (1,1,1,1)
%t A390674 stc[n_]:=Differences[Prepend[Join @@ Position[Reverse[IntegerDigits[n,2]],1],0]]//Reverse;
%t A390674 firsums[c_]:=Table[c[[i]]+c[[i+1]],{i,Length[c]-1}];
%t A390674 Select[Range[100],SameQ@@firsums[stc[#]]&]
